<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: 200 Haitians Request Asylum in 2 Years </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: 200 Haitians Request Asylum in 2 Years </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1406031194 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 12 Jun 94 p 3A </F>
<F P=103> PA1406031194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Manuel Alvarez Cedeno] </F>
  [Text] The National Office for Attention to Refugees 
[Oficina Nacional para la Atencion de los Refugiados, ONPAR] has 
reported that, since the Haitian political crisis broke out two 
years ago, approximately 200 Haitians have requested political 
asylum in Panama, but only 27 have qualified to receive it. 
  ONPAR Director Jose Javier Mulino told LA PRENSA that, since 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide was ousted, some 200 Haitians have 
requested refuge in Panama and that, of these, only 27 have 
qualified and nine cases are currently under study. 
  "We studied all the requests and confirmed that only 27 are 
classified as victims of political persecution by the regime of 
dictator Raoul Cedras," Mulino explained. The ONPAR conducts 
these analyses jointly with officials of the Endara 
administration and the UNHCR office. Mulino explained that to 
obtain political asylum the person must prove he is truly being 
politically persecuted. 

</TEXT>

