<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ibero-American Heads of State Summit Opens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ibero-American Heads of State Summit Opens </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on Salinas Address </H4>

<F P=102> PA1506021694 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1506021694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Oscar Navarro from Cartagena de Indias; from the </F>
"ACIR Radio News" newscast -- live] 
  [Text] During his speech to the Fourth Ibero-American 
Summit of heads of state and government, President Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari suggested the signing of more bilateral and 
multilateral agreements in the region as a new concept of 
integration among all the countries of the continent and 
Ibero-America. Speaking at the convention center in Cartagena 
de Indias, Colombia, the Mexican president explained the reasons 
our country had for diversifying its relations and for promoting 
domestic efforts for reforms, similar to what is happening in 
other nations. However, Carlos Salinas de Gortari warned that 
diversification of relations should not be an excuse to distract 
commercial flow. Let us hear what he said: 
  [Begin Salinas recording] Other Ibero-American nations have 
implemented plans in accordance to the needs of their people. 
This encourages shared purposes. Efforts for integration among 
our nations should not be an excuse to distract commercial flow 
nor to appear as blocs closed to exchange. Compatible with 
GATT, we can reach agreements that will be the motors of our 
economic activity, investment, creation of jobs, and 
distribution of income, which in the end is the important thing. 
[end recording] 
  The Mexican president also stressed that there must be 
greater recognition of the unilateral efforts for opening and 
change which must be expanded to areas such as services, labor, 
and the environment, all of which are factors for progress, 
greater coordination of monetary policies, exchange of 
technology, and shared production to strengthen commercial 
openings and investment. President Salinas de Gortari said that 
Ibero-America must use its influence in the multilateral forums, 
especially in the new trade organization. The president said 
that our priority today is the well-being of those who have less 
because it is not possible to advance with inefficient and 
isolated economies, nor can progress be made with 
internationalized economies that are socially irresponsible. 
For this reason, Salinas de Gortari said that we must insist on 
an economic recovery that goes hand in hand with well-thought 
and balanced social reforms, with democratic progress in 
pluralism. 
  Today's speeches by Salvadoran President Armando Calderon 
Sol, Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera, and Argentine 
President Carlos Menem, were also very important. They 
suggested an opening for the Cuban people's democracy. This 
could be important in strengthening peace and stability in the 
region. Fidel Castro did not broach this issue; however, he was 
very clear in stating that the U.S. blockade on Cuba must end. 
This is what he said: 
  [Begin Castro recording] In conclusion, this is an excellent 
opportunity to demand that the U.S. Government abide by the UN 
resolution on the criminal and unjust blockade against Cuba. 
[end recording] 
  I also wish to add that today's Colombian newspapers, 
especially the Cartagena de Indias newspapers, did not give much 
coverage to the summit. Instead they reported that the 
Colombian soccer team traveled to the United States today to 
participate in the World Cup. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

