<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ibero-American Heads of State Summit Opens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ibero-American Heads of State Summit Opens </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Honduras' Reina Urges Integration </H4>

<F P=102> PA1506034394 Paris AFP in Spanish 2309 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1506034394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cartagena, Colombia, 14 Jun (AFP) -- Honduran 
President Carlos Roberto Reina, during the first working session 
of the Fourth Ibero-American Summit in Cartagena today, called 
for a human-oriented economic integration process. He pointed 
out that the foreign debt continues to be a heavy burden for the 
Central American nations. 
  The leader seemed less optimistic about the region's 
economic 
recovery during the last few years than his other 20 
Ibero-American colleagues. Reina said that it was still 
impossible to speak of the expansion of economic recovery. 
  The Honduran president said "we must recognize that poverty 
has increased in the region." This is the first Ibero-American 
leaders' meeting he has attended, as the group has already 
gathered in the previous three consecutive years: in Guadalajara 
(Mexico), Madrid (Spain), and Salvador de Bahia (Brazil). 
  He added that "we must work toward an Ibero-American 
community with organizations that have the power to decide." He 
stressed that regional economic integration must not be the only 
priority, as the process must also include other important 
social issues. 
  Reina demanded "equal treatment" from the international 
financial institutions for Central America, whose leaders he 
encouraged to unite and to negotiate trade and commercial 
agreements with the rest of the continent as a bloc. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34007 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat115aa_94012" </HT>


