BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, Jun 14 (AFP) -- This Tuesday, 
Jean-Claude Martineau, spokesman of exiled President 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide, condemned the 12 June state of emergency 
proclamation by provisional President Emile Jonassaint (the 
international does not recognize him), describing it as a 
"Duvalierist diatribe and a threat veiled in demagoguery." 
  In a communique forwarded to the AFP office in 
Port-au-Prince, Martineau says "the country is, in fact, living 
amid a state of emergency, and all the people's rights have been 
suspended since 30 September 1991" (date of the coup d'etat.) 
"If you want to find those who threaten the country's 
independence, you will not find them abroad because they are in 
our country," he added. 

