<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Chief's Brother Asks Cedras To Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Chief's Brother Asks Cedras To Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1406201394 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1900 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1406201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Evans Francois, brother of the Port-au-Prince police 
chief, has asked General Cedras to resign to avoid a military 
intervention against Haiti. The brother of Lieutenant Colonel 
Michel Francois addressed a letter to that effect to the Army 
chief. Let us listen to Evans Francois: 
  [Begin Francois recording] At this watershed where my 
country's sovereignty is threatened by the most powerful nation 
in the world, General, the threats of military intervention are 
serious. This is not the time to be shilly-shallying. The 
courageous Evans, one of the authors of the 30 September coup 
d'etat, could have continued to give you his support. He was 
convinced you would have changed in a positive direction one 
day. If tomorrow, I were sure to find even a minimum of 
seriousness in your behavior... [pauses] What I am sure of, Mr. 
General, is that the 34 months of crisis have never been managed 
in the interest of the nation. There was not one government that 
came from the 30 September coup which, once installed, was not 
handicapped by your shrewd behavior, which always made you 
appear in the eyes of the world as a moderate, until appointment 
of the Jonassaint government, the disguised triumvirate. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

