<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Troops Assist Earthquake Victims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Troops Assist Earthquake Victims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1406170094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2122 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1406170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Panama, 12 Jun (ACAN-EFE) -- U.S. Army South, based 
in the Panama Canal area, today sent 37 troops in two "CH-47 
Chinook" helicopters to Colombia to help victims of the 
earthquake and subsequent floods, which have left several towns 
mired in mud. 
  A U.S. Army South communique says the troops sent to 
Colombia 
are specialists in meteorology, air traffic control, 
civilian-military operations, security, and medical treatment. 
The U.S. troops' mission is to transport Colombian Government 
first aid personnel and supplies and to evacuate disaster 
victims. 
  The Neiva Airport in Colombia is serving as an operations 
center and a storage center for supplies that will later be 
transported by helicopter to affected areas that are 
inaccessible by land following last week's earthquake. 
  The strong earthquake, which resulted in hundreds of deaths 
and disappearances early this week, was part of a wave of 
earthquakes that "bounced" among Bolivia, Chile, Peru, Paraguay, 
Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, Panama, Puerto Rico, the United 
States, and Canada. Earthquakes have recently increased in the 
so-called "circle of fire" in the Pacific, which includes all 
countries on the Pacific coast. 

</TEXT>

