<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Conducts Counternarcotics Operations in 21 States </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Conducts Counternarcotics Operations in 21 States </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1406161694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0905 GMT 11 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1406161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 11 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- The Mexican 
Secretariat of National Defense reported that various national 
institutions are conducting counternarcotics operations this 
rainy season, a time suitable for the planting of drug crops. 
  According to a communique issued by the Secretariat this 
Friday, Mexican troops have conducted operations in Mexico, 
Sinaloa, Durango, Chihuahua, Nayarit, Jalisco, Colima, 
Michoacan, Oaxaca, Nuevo Leon, Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Hidalgo, 
Guerrero, Zacatecas, Aguascalientes, San Luis de Potosi, 
Guanajuato, Queretaro, Puebla, and Morelos States. In the 
communique, the Secretariat of Defense indicated that these 
operations were not carried out solely in Guerrero State, where 
local media reported a "massive troop presence." 
  The communique indicated that operations staged in 21 states 
on 1 June resulted in the arrest of 10 local drug traffickers, 
the destruction of 2,242 drug crops, four drug traffickers' 
camps, and a marijuana drier. Officials also incinerated 323 kg 
of marijuana seeds, 30 kg of poppy seeds, and 2 kg of cocaine 
and confiscated 233 firearms and two vehicles. 
  The institution said that in addition to the 
counternarcotics 
operations, authorities will also apply the "Federal Law on 
Weapons and Control of Explosives." 
  The Secretariat added that following the "Regional Operation 
1- 94," conducted from 10 March to 5 April, 22,418 poppy and 
marijuana fields, 6,000 kg of marijuana, and 431 kg of poppy and 
marijuana seeds were destroyed. In addition, 256 firearms and 28 
vehicles were seized. The Secretariat of National Defense 
stated it is continuing its counternarcotics operations. 

</TEXT>

