<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Statistics Institute Examines Poverty Levels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Statistics Institute Examines Poverty Levels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0806233094 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 7 
Jun 94 p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0806233094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Almost half of the 9 million destitute Brazilian 
families live in the northeastern region: 48.67 percent of the 
region's inhabitants make hardly enough money to buy basic 
foodstuffs. These figures were released by the IBGE [Brazilian 
Institute of Geography and Statistics]. A diagram of Brazilian 
poverty levels and concentration prepared by the IBGE will be 
exhibited at the entrance hall of the Petrobras [Brazilian 
Petroleum Corporation] building until 10 June. The IBGE has 
also verified that misery exists everywhere in the country. The 
most developed Brazilian region -- the southeast -- has the 
second largest number of destitute people in the country, with a 
total of 2.6 million destitute families, i.e., almost 29 percent 
of the overall number. 
  According to IBGE, there is great social imbalance in the 
southeast region. The highest levels of poverty in this region 
are concentrated in the states of Minas Gerais, Espirito Santo, 
and Rio de Janeiro, while the lowest levels are in Sao Paulo 
State. In absolute figures, however, the largest number of 
shantytowns in the country are located in Sao Paulo State -- 594 
-- but only 6.8 percent of the state's population live in them. 
  Recife, Pernambuco State, is the great champion in this sad 
race. Almost half of its inhabitants -- 48.8 percent -- live in 
shantytowns. Among the state capitals, Salvador has the lowest 
number of inhabitants living in shantytowns: only 4 percent. 
Twenty-five percent of the northeastern region destitute, or 1.2 
million poor people, however, live in Bahia State. In Rio de 
Janeiro County, for example, 16.5 percent of the inhabitants are 
destitute. In Rio de Janeiro State, however, there are 661 
shantytowns. In Minas Gerais State, the city with the largest 
number of destitute people is not Belo Horizonte but Betim, 
where 15.5 percent of the people live in shantytowns. 
  According to Dora Hees, an IBGE geographer, the figures for 
the southern region have surprised IBGE experts: 14 percent of 
the overall destitute people in the country live in the region, 
most of them in the states of Parana and Rio Grande do Sul. 
Hees said: "The southern region has been revealing unexpected 
poverty conditions." She explained that the land distribution 
and modernization of agricultural production have been 
contributing to expelling the people from the countryside. 
  Surprisingly, the IBGE figures show that the urban zones of 
the northern region have the best standard of living in the 
country. The largest number of destitute families in the region 
-- 39,638 -- live in Belem, Para State. Six and one-half 
percent of the Brazilian poor live in the central-western 
region, most of them -- 55,610 families -- in the Federal 
District. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

