<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1106032694 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>
<F P=103> PY1106032694 </F>
<F P=104>  -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Brazil monitored through 9 
June. 
  The inflation rate calculated by the Economic Research 
Institute Foundation, Fipe, indicates a 1.12 percent drop 
compared to the April rate. The most accentuated drop was in 
the price of foodstuffs, which increased 44.4 percent in April 
and only 37.59 percent in May. The price of beef increased 22 
percent, well below the level of inflation, while the price of 
beans decreased 8 percent. The May Average General Price Index, 
IGP-M, measured by the Getulio Vargas Foundation, totalled 42.58 
percent and was lower than expected. (Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO 
BRASIL in Portuguese 7 Jun 94 p 1) 
  Science and Technology Minister Israel Vargas has reported 
that President Itamar Franco authorized an amendment to the 
budget allowing the allocation of $120 million of privatization 
resources to science and technology projects. He said that in 
addition to 30 percent of all Bank of Brazil Foundation 
resources, the $300 million in loans granted by the 
Inter-American Development Bank will also be assigned to the 
sector -- $200 million to finance scientific and technological 
development projects at Brazilian private companies, and $100 
million to the official research organizations. (Rio de Janeiro 
JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 2 Jun 94 p 8) 

</TEXT>

