<H3> <TI>   Central America Grants Nicaragua Special Trade Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central America Grants Nicaragua Special Trade Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1406212194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1839 GMT 14 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1406212194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cartagena de Indias, 14 Jun (PL) -- Nicaraguan 
President Violeta Barrios de Chamorro announced here today that 
the Central American nations have granted her country most 
favored nation status, according to the agreements reached this 
past weekend. 
  The decision was reached during a meeting between the 
Central 
American presidents, just hours before leaving together for this 
Colombian City, to attend the Fourth Ibero-American Summit. The 
Nicaraguan leader did not disclose the details of the agreement. 
  In her speech before the 21 other participating leaders, 
Violeta Barrios fiercely defended the privatization process, 
while downplaying the poverty situation in Latin America, 
particularly in Nicaragua. 
  In an address tainted by many diction errors and mistaken 
names and places, the leader used the better part of the seven 
minutes granted to each president, to overestimate the 
Nicaraguan democratic situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

