<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Defends Right To Present Opinions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robaina Defends Right To Present Opinions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606002694 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2119 GMT 15 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1606002694 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Juan Carlos Alfonso] </F>
  [Text] Cartagena de Indias, 15 Jun (PL) -- Cuban Foreign 
Minister Roberto Robaina today defended his country's right to 
present its viewpoints and opinions within the pluralist 
context, which should distinguish the discussions among the 
Ibero-American leaders. 
  During a news conference with Cuban reporters, the minister 
said the island has its own opinion on issues such as democracy 
and human rights, saying: "If these issues are to be discussed, 
my country has plenty to say." 
  Robaina said "the important thing is the possibility of 
having opinions and points of view on issues that can lead to 
discussions; in this way we would be taking advantage of the 
Colombian Government's suggestion to turn the working sessions 
into true debates, not just be limited to previously prepared 
statements brought from outside." 
  Robaina affirmed the Cuban delegation has received dozens of 
messages congratulating it for the way the chief of the Cuban 
revolution "took the bull by the horns" in his speech late 
yesterday. In his address, Fidel Castro thanked Brazilian 
President Itamar Franco for broaching the issue of the U.S. 
blockade against the island. 
  The chief of Cuba's diplomacy said "Cuba did not come to 
Cartagena to hear a unanimous acceptance of our opinions but, 
rather, to have them included in the process of analysis as 
well. We have the right and the experience to express our 
opinion." 
  The monotony of the meetings was broken when Cuban President 
Fidel Castro cited the issue of the U.S. blockade against his 
country, which the United Nations has condemned. 
  The Cuban leader's participation created great expectation, 
as it is expected this issue, and several others the island's 
delegation presented, will be discussed during the last portion 
of the presidents' session, which continues behind closed doors. 

</TEXT>

