<H3> <TI>   Mexican Opposition to Blockade Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mexican Opposition to Blockade Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1506132294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0029 GMT 15 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1506132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 14 Jun (PL) -- Today, official sources 
reported that the Chamber of Deputies expressed its support here 
for any initiative to lift the U.S. blockade of Cuba. 
  Referring to relations between Cuba and Washington, the 
legislature released a communique on Tuesday stating that 
differences "are not solved by unilateral and interventionist 
means." 
  Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) Deputy Fernando 
Charleston read a statement stressing that the blockade of Cuba 
is a violation of essential principles of international law, 
especially nonintervention. 
  Charleston also confirmed that the document issued by the 
Chamber of Deputies expresses solidarity with the Cuban people 
in defense of their sovereignty and self-determination. 
  A state's decision to establish commercial ties with another 
state, the deputy added, is an expression of its sovereignty and 
should not be subordinated to the will of a foreign government. 
For Mexico, nonintervention in the domestic affairs of another 
nation and respect for ideologies are aspects that should rule 
their relations, he said. 
  Meanwhile, Luis Beauregard, also of the PRI, announced that 
the statement approved on Tuesday by the Chamber of Deputies 
will be sent to governments friendly with Mexico as well as to 
those nations that are currently discussing an end to the 
commercial blockade of that island. 

</TEXT>

