<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Reiterates Opposition to Occupations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reiterates Opposition to Occupations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606011294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2324 GMT 15 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1606011294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 15 Jun (PL) -- Cuba reiterated today before 
the diplomatic corps accredited in this country its opposition 
to the illegal occupation of diplomatic missions by people who 
want to abandon the country. 
  The Foreign Ministry [Minrex] summoned the heads of the 
foreign missions and briefed them on the current situation 
regarding the presence of three groups that forced their way a 
few days ago into the residence of the Belgian ambassador and 
the German Embassy, as well as the Chilean consulate. 
  Minrex Spokesman Miguel Alonso later told the local and 
foreign media that according to Cuba the firmness by all the 
sides affected by these incident favors a possible prompt 
solution. 
  Nine people, including a woman and a child, participated in 
the most recent illegal entry, which occurred at the Chilean 
Consulate. 
  Alonso explained the Cuban Government has reiterated to the 
ambassadors its decision to help resolve the problem caused by 
the occupants of their respective buildings. He ruled out any 
legal action against those who voluntarily leave. 
  Those transgressions cannot replace the country's current 
normal procedure to travel abroad, nor is it acceptable to try 
to force an ambassador into granting a visa, he added. 
  During the meeting, Cuba reaffirmed that in accordance with 
international agreements, it respects the sanctity of embassies 
and offers protection to all missions accredited in this 
Caribbean nation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

