<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1506192894 </F>
<F P=103> PA1506192894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 15 June. 
  The Salvadoran Coffee Council, CSC, reported that coffee 
exports during the past eight months had surpassed $120.2 
million. According to the CSC, this amount corresponds to 
1,031,735 sacks of coffee, each weighing 69 kgs, exported from 
10 October 1993 to 13 June 1994. It is part of the 1993-94 
coffee harvest period. Receiving countries include Germany, 
Belgium, Canada, Spain, Finland, France, Holland, Hong Kong, the 
UK, Italy, Japan, Norway, Portugal and the United States. CSC 
Executive Director Ruben Ernesto Pinto stated the current coffee 
harvest, despite being less than the 1992-93 period, will result 
in greater revenues for the country because of rising prices in 
the international markets. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1838 
GMT 14 Jun 94) 
  According to recent official figures, during the past two 
years El Salvador recorded average annual GDP growth rates of at 
least 5 percent and has become one of the Latin American 
countries with the highest growth rate. After the signing of 
the January 1992 peace agreement between the government and the 
guerrillas which brought an end to the 12-year-old internal 
conflict, El Salvador implemented a process of political 
stabilization that reverberated in the country's economic 
growth. GDP, which in 1989 was merely 1.1 percent, increased to 
5.1 percent in 1992, and by 1993 real economic growth was 5.0 
percent. According to Central Reserve Bank of El Salvador, BCR, 
figures, GDP recorded growth rates during the first two months 
of the year totalled 7.2 percent. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in 
Spanish 2343 GMT 8 Jun 94) 
  Recent official figures indicate that currency mailed by 
Salvadorans living overseas, mainly in the United States, to 
their relatives in El Salvador surpassed export revenues by 
$152.3 million during 1993. A BCR spokesman pointed out that 
during 1993, currency mailed to relatives totalled $884 million, 
while export revenues amounted to $731.7 million. During the 
first quarter of the current year, revenue originating from 
Salvadorans living in the United States has so far totalled 
$223.2 million. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2316 GMT 8 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

