<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606003594 </F>
<F P=103> PA1606003594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 15 June. 
  The National Economic Council has decided to cut the 
national 
investment budget by $198 million because of the international 
financial institution's, IFI's, decision to withhold funds from 
Panama, including a loan from the Japanese Government that is 
tied to a World Bank loan. The reason for this decision is that 
Panama has failed to meet certain IFI conditions. (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 7 Jun 94) 
  President Guillermo Endara has reported that at a special 
cabinet meeting on 9 June, it was decided that there will be 
budget cuts in all ministries totalling $269.6 million. Endara 
explained that the 1994 budget has been balanced, but that all 
ministries will face cuts. The ministries that will be most 
affected are health, housing, public works, education, finance, 
and agricultural development. The reason for the cuts, Endara 
explained, is that the IFI's have suspended the disbursement of 
approximately $270 million because Panama has failed to meet 
certain requirements, including reducing the state payroll. 
Most of the cuts will be in the area of investments. (Panama 
City LA PRENSA in Spanish 10 Jun 94 p 1) 
  Planning Minister Delia Cardenas and Health Minister Jose 
Remon have sent a letter to Lewis T. Preston, president of the 
International Reconstruction and Development Bank, detailing 
Panama's lingering poverty problem. The letter states that 
although the Panamanian economy is making great strides, the gap 
between the social classes is widening and poverty remains at 
approximately 44 percent. Cardenas and Remon explain that 
Panama's economy grew by 9.6 percent in 1991, 8.6 percent in 
1992, and approximately 5.9 percent in 1993. In 1992, the 
country's per capita GDP rose to $2,412 and investments 
increased 20.4 percent. The letter explains that the 
government's 1994 investment program earmarks 43 percent of its 
resources for social projects and that Panama is one of the 
Latin American governments that spend the most on health. The 
letter says an effort should be made to reduce poverty to 30 or 
35 percent. (Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 9 Jun 94 p 15A) 
  The National Bank of Panama collected more than $165 million 
in capital during the first four months of 1994, overcoming the 
$1.2 million deficit of early 1990. The bank has announced that 
its private deposits increased from $158 million in December 
1980 to $230.6 million on 30 April 1994. The bank's liquid 
assets also increased from 9.7 percent in December 1989 to 61.5 
percent on 30 April 1994. (Panama City Circuito RPC Television 
in Spanish 2300 GMT 7 Jun 94) 
  Federico Humbert, a successful Panamanian businessman, has 
accepted President-elect Ernesto Perez Balladares' challenge to 
head an executive office that will promote new foreign 
investments in Panama. Addressing members of the Inter-American 
Press Association, Perez Balladares said the purpose of the new 
office is to change Panama's bureaucratic mindset to one that 
will seek foreign capital and be more aggressive. Meanwhile, 
Humbert said: "I believe the new government has shown signs that 
it will favor a national concerted effort, which is what we all 
want to make Panama better for more Panamanians." (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 7 Jun 94) 
  During May, the Colon Free Zone's cumulative sales totalled 
$4.131 billion, according to Free Zone statistics. Compared with 
the same period in 1993, overall sales increased 15.3 percent; 
imports increased 14.1 percent; and exports increased 16.4 
percent. (Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 10 Jun 94 p 13A) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

