<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary on Castro's Attire, Stand at Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary on Castro's Attire, Stand at Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1506215694 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1506215694 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary] </F>
  [Text] Undoubtedly, clothes do not make the man. This can 
be confirmed by those who, yesterday, applauded when they saw 
the Cuban president arrive at the Fourth Ibero-American Summit 
with a smile on his face and looking slim. It would take less 
than an hour to thwart all the conjectures concerning the 
clothes worn by the leader of the Cuban Revolution. For the 
first time, he abandoned his olive green uniform to wear a 
typical Cuban guayabera. 
  His firm and courageous words, as on previous occasions when 
he stood at a national or international podium, dashed the 
assumptions of those who believed the change in attire indicated 
the Cuban position was crumbling. His direct, profound, accurate 
speech concentrated on denouncing the evils that afflict our 
America and those responsible for so much sorrow and poverty. He 
is the same Fidel -- profoundly Latin American, defender of the 
poor and disenfranchised, a courageous fighter against causes, 
or anything that obstructs Latin American development. 
  If there is any other possible interprepation for the 
clothes 
he wore at the Fourth Ibero-American Summit, it would be only 
that the guayabera is an article of Cuban clothing; it is in 
great taste; it was created near the Yayabo River; and its wear 
has become mandatory among Latin Americans. Therefore, it is 
another symbol, another part of our roots on which we stand in 
this hour. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34139 </DOCNO>
