<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Sets 7 Aug as Date for Referendum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Sets 7 Aug as Date for Referendum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1506234094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0255 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1506234094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Quito, 15 Jun (EFE) -- The Ecuadoran Government 
today set 7 August as the date for the referendum which 
President Sixto Duran-Ballen announced on 10 June and which most 
of the opposition political forces in the country have described 
as illegal. During a radio and television network today, an 
announcer just announced the date for the referendum and read 
the seven-question questionnaire Duran-Ballen presented three 
days ago. The results of the referendum will decide whether 
another plebiscite will be held on 2 January 1995. This second 
plebiscite will be held to learn of the people's wishes 
regarding the summoning of a constituent assembly to make 
changes to the Constitution. 
  "Our most heartfelt wish is to make actual changes to the 
social, political, economic, and moral plans," President 
Duran-Ballen said during last week's radio and television 
network. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

