<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1506232494 </F>
<F P=103> PA1506232494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Venezuelan economic developments monitored through 15 
June. 
  The government has announced that the Aeropostal airline 
will 
be put on public bid once again within 90 days. If during this 
time it is not privatized, the company will be closed down, 
because currently it is producing a loss of about 20 million 
bolivars daily. (Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
7 Jun 94) 
  Gustavo Roosen, presidential commissioner for financial 
reform, has reported that of the 750 billion bolivars granted as 
financial aid by FOGADE [Deposit Guarantee and Banking 
Protection Fund], only 30 percent will be recovered, because it 
would be unwise to sell the assets of the banks FOGADE is 
supporting. If the assets were to be sold, the market would be 
flooded with property, thereby hurting the construction sector. 
(Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 9 Jun 94) 
  Venezuelan Petroleum Inc. (PDVSA) has reported that the 
production of crude is growing at an annual rate of about 7 
percent in 1994. PDVSA also indicated that between 1992 and 1994 
annual investments of $3.5 billion have been made in this sector 
and that 1993 closed without a deficit. (Caracas EL NACIONAL in 
Spanish 9 Jun 94 p E-3) 
  Acting Finance Minister Luis Xavier Grisanti has reported 
that fiscal revenues for the 1994 budget have been reestimated 
at 1.55 trillion bolivars, representing a 322 billion increase 
from last year. (Caracas EL NACIONAL in Spanish 9 Jun 94 p E-3) 
  The Finance Ministry has reported that 17.6 billion bolivars 
were collected as part of the new Bank Debit Tax debits in the 
first month of its application. The ministry also reported that 
the financial crisis unleashed by the Banco Latino intervention 
has caused uncertainly among the public, which has been 
reflected in the exchange rate and caused a demand for dollars 
that exceeds the needs of the nation's normal economic 
transactions. (Caracas ECONOMIA HOY in Spanish 10 Jun 94 p 8) 
  Berend Roosen, president of the National Council of Commerce 
and Services, has said merchants remain very concerned about the 
devaluation of the bolivar and increasing interest rates. Both 
factors are prompting higher prices, inflation, a decline in 
sales, and a loss of purchasing power, thereby forcing many 
merchants to close their shops. (Caracas ECONOMIA HOY in Spanish 
10 Jun 94 p 10) 
  According to estimates diclosed Saturday, the recovery of 
petroleum prices in recent weeks will provide for additional 
revenues of $242 million for Venezuela. In addition, revenues in 
May increased by approximately $120 million. (Paris AFP in 
Spanish 1636 GMT 11 Jun 94) 
  According to Inter-American Development Bank sources, 
Venezuela has been granted 50 loans for a total of $3.501 
billion, registering disbursements of $1.694 billion to be paid 
out in 10 years. Part of this loan will used to construct a 
power station with an installed capacity of 2.160 megawatts, and 
in which environmental aspects have been taken into account. 
(Caracas EL UNIVERSAL in Spanish 11 Jun 94 p 2) 
  An official report today indicated that between 2,500 and 
3,000 small and medium-sized industries that have debts of more 
than $1 billion risk going bankrupt. The debts of the industries 
that provide jobs for approximately 100,000 people is unpayable 
by the debtors under the current conditions, according to a 
Development Ministry document. The report indicates that massive 
bankruptcies could be unleashed, which in turn would increase 
the current registered unemployment rate of 22 percent. (Mexico 
City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0121 GMT 14 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

