<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Speeches to Ibero-American Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Speeches to Ibero-American Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Salvadoran President on Development </H4>

<F P=102> PA1506184994 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 0300 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1506184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cartagena -- Salvadoran President Armando Calderon 
Sol on 14 June in Cartagena urged his colleagues meeting in the 
Fourth Ibero-American Summit of Heads of State and Government to 
form a common front to defend the legitimate right to 
development of the region's peoples. 
  He said that strengthening representative democracy, 
promoting human rights, and achieving economic and social 
development should be the great goals of the 21 Ibero-American 
leaders. 
  President Calderon, who is attending for the first time the 
meeting of Ibero-American leaders, a group that has already met 
on three occasions, added that now that nearly all peoples of 
the region are enjoying democracy, it is crucial that we direct 
our efforts toward improving the living conditions of our 
people. He called for an expanded discussion among the 
presidents on the integration issue, not just on trade 
liberalization. Calderon pointed out that our Central American 
countries are making enormous efforts toward integration. 

</TEXT>

