<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidents, Officials React to Castro Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidents, Officials React to Castro Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    De Leon, Figueres on Castro </H4>

<F P=102> PA1506211094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1705 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1506211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cartagena de Indias (Colombia), 15 Jun (EFE) -- 
Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon Carpio and Costa Rican 
President Jose Figueres stated today that they respect but do 
not share the opinion of their colleague Fidel Castro, who 
reproached the participants of the Ibero-American Summit for not 
saying "a single word" about the U.S. embargo against Cuba. 
  "I respect the opinion of President Castro, but do not agree 
with it, nor do I agree with his concept of what democracy is," 
de Leon told a group of newsmen. The Guatemalan president added 
that he does not feel he was recriminated by Castro at the 
summit. Castro also complained that the summit has not 
recognized the fact that Cuba is the Ibero-American country 
which has achieved the most in social aspects. 
  Asked about the same topic, Figueres responded that the 
Cuban 
president's statements "are his opinion, but not those of the 
other presidents," and that he respects all opinions. The Costa 
Rican president also said the political situations of Cuba and 
Haiti, which will be broached today by the chiefs of states and 
governments and their foreign ministers at a closed-door 
meeting, complicate the continent's integration processes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34202 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat116aa_94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-116 </AU>
