<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Summit Leader Speeches on 14 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Summit Leader Speeches on 14 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Guatemala's De Leon Seeks Support </H4>

<F P=102> PA1606153694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1748 GMT 14 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1606153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cartagena de Indias, 14 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- Guatemalan 
President Ramiro De Leon Carpio today thanked the Ibero-American 
nations for their solidarity during the peace negotiations with 
the guerrillas and urged them to prevent the talks from becoming 
bogged down. 
  During the first session of the Fourth Ibero-American Summit 
of heads of state and government, De Leon Carpio said that 
"there is a glimmer of light at the end of the tunnel" and that 
despite the difficulty of the negotiations the Guatemalan 
Government is determined to fulfill its moral commitment. 
  "On 29 March we signed a negotiations agreement-schedule, 
which underscores such points as the cease-fire in September and 
the demobilization of the guerrillas in December and which 
confirms that the signing of peace in 1994 is irreversible," De 
Leon Carpio said. 
  The Guatemalan president told the leaders of 21 countries, 
including the Dominican vice president, that he hopes to be 
remembered as the president whose administration established 
"total respect for the law and the conviction that that is the 
best attitude." "We have made considerable progress by signing 
the general agreement on human rights and immediate 
international verification," the president added. 
  The Guatemalan president pointed out that "with the end of 
the 30-year-old internal armed confrontation -- the leading 
source of human rights violations -- we will achieve total 
respect for life and individual guarantees." After urging 
Ibero-America to allow the opening of markets and the 
elimination of protectionist barriers, De Leon Carpio said: "We 
can set the example by trading among ourselves and later 
requesting similar conditions from the rest of the international 
community." 
  According to the Guatemalan president, Central America is 
attempting to reduce its huge social disparities, improve its 
peoples' standard of living through democratic consolidation and 
productive transformations, and increase its participation in 
worldwide trade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34229 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat117aa_94017" </HT>


