<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balaguer Opposes Military Intervention in Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balaguer Opposes Military Intervention in Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606201494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1924 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1606201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 16 Jun (EFE) -- Dominican President 
Joaquin Balaguer today expressed his opposition to a military 
intervention in Haiti to oust the military government that 
overthrew Jean-Bertrand Aristide in September 1991. 
Nevertheless, he warned that the Dominican Government is 
prepared to protect the joint border. 
  Balaguer said he is confident that due to the Latin American 
government's rejection of an invasion, the international 
community will not reach the extreme of invading Haiti. 
  He said dialogue between the two sides in conflict in Haiti 
could contribute to the return of democracy in that country and 
he explained that Dominican authorities are ready to defend and 
protect the 386-km border shared with Haiti on the island of 
Hispaniola, in case of a military invasion. 
  Balaguer has repeatedly opposed the embargo imposed on Haiti 
by the international community. Nevertheless, since the end of 
May there has been strict compliance with the sanctions, to the 
point of preventing Haitians from obtaining food and medicine in 
the Dominican Republic. The Dominican president has ordered 
approximately 15,000 soldiers to guard the border with Haiti to 
prevent the violation of the international embargo against that 
country. Border surveillance intensified after Balaguer held 
several meetings with UN and U.S. officials in Santo Domingo. 
The heavy border surveillance, which prevents Haitians and 
Dominicans from trading on the border, has caused at least three 
Haitian deaths in the past 15 days during attacks on Dominican 
soldiers who prevent Haitians from crossing the border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
