<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   10,000 Demonstrate in Chiapas for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    10,000 Demonstrate in Chiapas for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606172894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1606 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1606172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Mexico City, 16 Jun (EFE) -- More than 10,000 
people today took part in a demonstration called by the Crusade 
for Peace. The demonstration, which followed the Zapatist 
National Liberation Army's [EZLN] refusal to sign a peace 
agreement, took place in Tuxtla Gutierrez, capital of Chiapas. 
  The demonstration came four days after the EZLN announced 
that it will not accept the government's response to its demands 
and that it will not sign a peace agreement in Chiapas. Most of 
the demonstrators wore white clothes, which, according to them, 
symbolize their hope for restoring peace in the state, and they 
asked that war be avoided because it will only engender more 
misery. 
  Jose Perez, leader of the Tzotzil, one of three major Indian 
groups in the area, indicated that his people want to live in 
peace and that they plan to respect the law, as long as it is 
fair and equitable. 
  Perez stressed that peace begins with respect for the law, 
adding: "We, Indians, have our own customs, which do not 
contradict the laws of the nation and which also deserve to be 
respected by the authorities." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

