<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Salinas on Peace Process, Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Salinas on Peace Process, Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606132194 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1606132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday, President Salinas said there is a 
national consensus on peace. He said the negative position the 
Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN] has expressed in 
Chiapas is more a political issue than a social problem. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] The peace process continues, and 
local organizations must ensure smooth progress. Allow me to 
say the efforts of the peace commissioner and the mediator have 
paved the way for the San Cristobal negotiations and certified 
the cease-fire. Their job was quite satisfactory and 
constituted a starting point for continued progress. 
  Allow me to say that despite not having a formal peace 
agreement yet, it is noteworthy to mention the cease-fire is 
still in effect, and both sides do prefer a political solution 
for peace. These two things, the cease-fire and the political 
solution, have been achieved. They confirm the strategy we 
chose to deal with the problem from the very beginning was in 
fact the correct one. 
  We have managed to build a national consensus in favor of 
peace. The EZLN's response seems to come from a more political 
decision than as the result of social or justice analyses. The 
federal government reaffirms the following: 
  1. We will proceed to ensure military security in the area 
and guarantee national sovereignty over the territory. 
  2. Current social programs will be reinforced, 
particularly for health and supplies. 
  3. Government institutions, organizations, parties, and 
society in general will participate in the continuing debate on 
the country's political and democratic progress, in accordance 
with the law. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

