<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister, Bank President on Paris Club Loans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister, Bank President on Paris Club Loans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606152194 Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1606152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Nicaragua will request $1.6 billion in loans from 
the Paris Club for the next three years. Before departing for 
Europe, Finance Minister Emilio Pereira and Central Bank 
President Evenor Taboada reported that the World Bank and IMF 
Boards of Directors will approve soft loans for Nicaragua next 
week. 
  In Paris, a government delegation headed by the Presidency 
minister will present to the delegates of 25 countries the 
country's economic strategy for the next three years. 
  [Begin recording] [Taboada] The agenda deals with 
Nicaragua's 
cooperation, reform, and modernization, the transformation of 
its social agenda, and its need for technical, economic, and 
social assistance. 
  [Pereira] Approximately $310 million of the $550 to $560 
million that we expect to borrow in 1994 has virtually been 
obtained. [end recording] 
  The officials reported that they will request a total of 
$1.6 
billion for the next three years. In addition, they reported 
that the IMF and the World Bank will approve loans soon. 
  [Begin Taboada recording] The IMF director and the World 
Bank 
Board of Directors on 22 and 23 June will study Nicaragua's 
request, after which we expect to receive the first 
disbursements. [end recording] 
  One of the subjects to be explained to the Paris Club is the 
progress attained in the solution of problems related to the 
confiscation of real estate owned by foreigners. 
  [Begin Pereira recording] We are confident there will be no 
problems. I am taking a report of all the cases that have been 
settled and whose solutions meet other countries' demands with 
me in my portfolio. [end recording] 
  The Presidency minister will fly to Paris tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

