<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   COPA Airline To Suspend Haiti Flights 26 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    COPA Airline To Suspend Haiti Flights 26 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1606164894 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 16 
Jun 94 p48 </F>

<F P=103> PA1606164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] The Compania Panamena de Aviacion (COPA) airline 
will suspend its two weekly flights to Haiti beginning on 26 
June to comply with UN sanctions. Deputy Foreign Minister 
Carlos G. Cordero announced the measure, stating that the 
suspension of flights to Haiti complies with the commercial 
blockade imposed by the United Nations and the OAS against the 
Raoul Cedras military regime. 
  Cordero told the media that yesterday, "acting President 
Guillermo Ford Boyd signed the decree establishing the 
prohibition of flights to Port-au-Prince effective 26 June." 
  COPA was the only Latin American airline covering the route 
to the Caribbean nation. Regarding this measure, a COPA source 
said the company does not yet have the official notification 
from the central government. The airline official said that 
General Manager Pedro Heilbron will be returning from a trip to 
Miami tomorrow and that Deputy Manager Moises Veliz is on 
vacation. 
  When LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA previously interviewed Heilbron, 
he said the company "will comply with the government's order as 
long as the U.S. airlines suspend their commercial flights to 
Haiti." 
  According to Heilbron, the U.S. companies "did not comply" 
with the previous two sanctions established by the international 
organizations against the Caribbean island. 
  The COPA flights to Haiti mainly carry Haitian businessmen 
and merchants coming to Panama to make purchases in the Colon 
Free Zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

